0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"page-wrap","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"className":"page-back","href":"/#research","children":[["$","svg",null,{"width":"16","height":"16","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","fill":"none","children":["$","path",null,{"d":"M10 3L5 8L10 13","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":"1.5","strokeLinecap":"round"}]}],"Back"]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"article-hero","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"research-meta","style":{"marginBottom":16},"children":[["$","span",null,{"children":"March 2026"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"·"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"12 min read"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"·"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"Distributed Systems"}]]}],["$","h1",null,{"children":"On Building Resilient Distributed Systems"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"article-content","children":[["$","p","0",{"children":"Distributed systems fail. That's not a flaw — it's a fundamental property of any system composed of independent components communicating over a network. The question isn't whether your system will experience partial failure, but whether it degrades gracefully when it does."}],["$","blockquote","1",{"children":"\"The network is reliable\" is the first of the eight fallacies of distributed computing. Every architecture decision you make should be stress-tested against its negation."}],["$","h2","2",{"children":"Designing for Failure Modes"}],["$","p","3",{"children":"Resilience starts before a single line of code is written. The most important exercise in distributed system design is enumerating failure modes — not to prevent them, but to understand how your system behaves when they occur."}],["$","p","4",{"children":"For every component in your architecture, ask: what happens when this is unavailable? What happens when it's slow? What happens when it returns incorrect results? The answers shape your circuit breakers, your retry logic, your fallback paths."}],["$","h2","5",{"children":"The Role of Idempotency"}],["$","p","6",{"children":"Retries are essential in distributed systems. Networks fail, services restart, timeouts happen. But retrying non-idempotent operations creates data consistency problems that are significantly harder to fix than the original failure."}],["$","p","7",{"children":"Design operations to be safe to repeat. Use idempotency keys for mutations. Build consumers that handle duplicate messages gracefully. This isn't defensive programming — it's foundational to building systems that can self-heal."}],["$","h2","8",{"children":"Observability as Infrastructure"}],["$","p","9",{"children":"You cannot reason about system behavior you cannot observe. Distributed tracing, structured logging, and fine-grained metrics aren't optional in complex systems — they're as important as the system itself."}],["$","p","10",{"children":"At Nest, we treat observability as a first-class concern from the first deployment. It's significantly harder to retrofit than to build in from the start."}]]}]]}],null,["$","$L3",null,{"children":["$","$4",null,{"name":"Next.MetadataOutlet","children":"$@5"}]}]]}],"isPartial":false,"staleTime":300,"varyParams":null,"buildId":"pyGCzhn3iTGD2__OF9WVo"}
